\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces What the policy recovers, physically (\texttt  {softmax}, the GA comparison benchmark). Both fabrics are drawn at the \emph  {same tile scale}. The traditional island-style baseline (left) is a $43\times 43$ heterogeneous fabric that provisions BRAM columns (plum) the netlist never uses, with DSP blocks (terracotta) spread across regular DSP columns. The RL-optimized fabric (right) tailors the architecture to the netlist: it drops the unused BRAM columns entirely, repositions the DSPs, and shrinks the array to $36\times 40$. The dashed outline is the traditional footprint and the hatched strip is the reclaimed area --- a $22\%$ smaller fabric, the dominant term in the $15\%$ ADP reduction. Gaps between tiles are routing channels.}}{6}{figure.caption.7}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:layout}{{3}{6}{What the policy recovers, physically (\texttt {softmax}, the GA comparison benchmark). Both fabrics are drawn at the \emph {same tile scale}. The traditional island-style baseline (left) is a $43\times 43$ heterogeneous fabric that provisions BRAM columns (plum) the netlist never uses, with DSP blocks (terracotta) spread across regular DSP columns. The RL-optimized fabric (right) tailors the architecture to the netlist: it drops the unused BRAM columns entirely, repositions the DSPs, and shrinks the array to $36\times 40$. The dashed outline is the traditional footprint and the hatched strip is the reclaimed area --- a $22\%$ smaller fabric, the dominant term in the $15\%$ ADP reduction. Gaps between tiles are routing channels}{figure.caption.7}{}}
